Maxillary apparatus lost, observed in paratype LACM-AHF POLY 6923. Maxillary apparatus with MF= 1+1, 6+7, 6+0, 4+9, 1+1. (
Fig. 15C
). Maxillary carriers 1.8 times shorter than length of MI. MI forceps-like; closing system 9 times shorter than length of MI; ligament between MI and MII not sclerotized (
Fig. 15C
). MII wide; teeth recurved, sharped; cavity opening oval, 6 times shorter than length of MII; ligament between MII and MIII, and right MIV, not sclerotized (
Fig. 15C
). MIII short; with triangular teeth; with attachment lamella slightly sclerotized (
Fig. 15C
). Left MIV with a smaller basal tooth; attachment not sclerotized. Right MIV with small teeth; attachment lamella not sclerotized (
Fig. 15C
). MV square, with a short triangular tooth (
Fig. 15C
). Mandibles translucent, cutting plates with 8 growth rings.

Branchiae pectinate with up to 15 filaments, in chaetigers 7–18 (
Figs. 15A
; 
16B
). Number of branchial filaments per chaetiger in order anterior-posterior: 8, 10, 12, 14, 15, 15, 14, 14, 14, 10, 10, 4. Last branchia smaller; branchial filaments longer than dorsal cirri.

First two parapodia smallest; most developed in chaetigers 3–17, following ones becoming gradually smaller. Notopodial cirri conical, increasing in size from chaetiger 4 (Ldc4: 
0.55 mm
; Ldc19: 
0.60 mm
), from chaetiger 22, gradually decreasing in width and increasing in length; in posterior region filiform, twice longer than pre-branchial region ones (Ldc92: 
1.1 mm
); Hayashi & Yamane’s organ present (
Fig. 16A–D
). Prechaetal lobes as a transverse fold in all chaetigers (
Fig. 16A–D
). Chaetal lobes in chaetigers 1–21, rounded, shorter than postchaetal lobes, with aciculae emerging dorsal to midline; from chaetiger 22, triangular, longer than other lobes, with acicula emerging in midline (
Fig. 16A–D
). Postchaetal lobes well developed in chaetiger 1–29, conical, thinner and longer in branchial region; decreasing in size in chaetigers 18–29, following ones inconspicuous (
Fig. 16A–D
). Ventral cirri conical in chaetigers 1–5; in chaetigers 6–22 with oval swollen base and digitiform tip; from chaetiger 23, conical, short (
Fig. 16A–D
).

Aciculae blunt, translucent (
Fig. 16A–D
). First 17 chaetigers with 3 aciculae; in chaetigers 18–22 with 2 aciculae; from chaetiger 23, with only one acicula.

Limbate chaetae of two sizes in same chaetiger, larger in anterior region, reduced in number around chaetiger 20. Two 
types
of pectinate chaetae; in anterior chaetigers, isodonts narrow with long and slender teeth, with 2–3 pectinate, with up to 6–9 teeth, with transverse distal edge (
Fig. 17E
); in median-posterior chaetigers, isodonts narrow with short and slender teeth, with 5–6 pectinate, with up to 15–16 teeth, with oblique distal edge (
Fig. 17F
). Compound spinigers in chaetigers 1–22, 10–12 per chaetiger, with all blades of similar size (
Fig. 17D
). Compound falcigers in all chaetigers, more abundant than spinigers; first 18 chaetigers with blades of two sizes (longer 73.5 µm, 
Fig. 17A
; smaller 66.5 µm, 
Fig. 17B
); all with triangular teeth, of similar size, distal tooth directed upward, proximal tooth directed laterally; in media-posterior chaetigers with all blades of similar size, shorter than blades of anterior chaetigers (39.2 µm, 
Fig. 17C
), with triangular teeth, distal tooth shorter than proximal, directed upward, proximal tooth directed laterally. Subacicular hooks bidentate, translucent, starting from chaetiger 21, with triangular teeth, distal tooth smaller than proximal, directed upward; proximal tooth directed laterally; several hooks per chaetiger: with 3 hooks in chaetiger 21, with 5 hooks in chaetigers 22–24, with 8 hooks in chaetigers 25– 30, with 10 hooks in chaetigers 31–42, with 10–14 hooks in chaetigers 43–73, with 10–7 hooks in chaetigers 74– 95; last five chaetigers with 5 hooks per chaetiger (
Fig. 18A–C
).
